\end{document} Density values characterize computational requirements. A tighter bound is provided by the so-called demand bound function (DBF):

The overall execution requirements of task τi over an interval [t0, t0 + t) are maximized if one of its jobs arrives at the start of the interval—i.e., at time instant t0—and its subsequent jobs arrive as rapidly as permitted, i.e., at instants t0 + Ti, t0 + 2Ti, t0 + 3Ti, …. This observation leads to Eq. (6.13) [39, 41]: 6.13DBF(τi,t)=max0,t−DiTi+1∗Ci\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
